Interactive Code Playgrounds

A slides system to make University programming classes more active and inclusive

Department of Information Engineering and Computer Science

University of Trento

Luca De Menego

01

Why?

Learning to code isn't easy.

Especially when first starting out.

We want to propose a solution
that rethinks one of the staples of programming classes.

What students said

  • "it's convenient"
  • "it's time-saving"
  • "it helps maintainining focus"
  • "it helps understanding the code better"
  • "it reveals my knowledge gaps"

Some quotes from students

"Being able to stay in the browser without having to use other programs is convenient as it allows you to follow the lecture without having to open, edit, save and minimize the development environment"

"Being able to make on-the-fly changes is useful to understand what each piece of code does"

Conclusions

Limitations

  • ICPs - some compatibility issues and missing features
  • Research - missing evaluation of challenging contexts and the tool's accessibility

Strengths

  • Engaging and productive pedagogy
  • Uniform environment
  • Front-end only
  • Inclusive by design

Interactive Code Playgrounds

A slides system to make University programming classes more active and inclusive

Background

A browser can be a useful tool to uniform the development environment

Development

ICPs are both slides and a frontend-only development environment requiring no installation

Results

Generally positive. Students particularly appreciated ICPs' resulting interactive pedagogy

Luca De Menego
